reply_split: To sum the info up simply:

thread_title: Tenergy 05 vs Tenergy 80
reply_split: 1) T05: Slower, More Spin, Higher Throw Angle.

thread_title: Tenergy 05 vs Tenergy 80
reply_split: 2) T64: Faster, Less Spin, Lower Throw Angle.

thread_title: Tenergy 05 vs Tenergy 80
reply_split: So do you want a bigger arc, more spin to spin the person off the table but a little sacrifice in speed?

thread_title: Tenergy 05 vs Tenergy 80
reply_split: Or do you want lower shots that don't come up as much and are faster.

thread_title: Tenergy 05 vs Tenergy 80
reply_split: But with an amount of spin that is easier to counter.

thread_title: Tenergy 05 vs Tenergy 80
reply_split: Or do you want to be half way in between the two extremes?

thread_title: Tenergy 05 vs Tenergy 80
reply_split: I go with slower and more spin every time.

thread_title: Tenenergy 05 vs Donic Baracuda
reply_split: Tenergy has a slightly higher throw angle than Baracuda, so looping heavy chops may be a little bit easier, with a greater arc on the ball.

thread_title: Tenenergy 05 vs Donic Baracuda
reply_split: However, Baracuda still has a medium-high throw so they're both perfectly fine for looping.

thread_title: Tenenergy 05 vs Donic Baracuda
reply_split: In my personal opinion, Baracuda has more spin than Tenergy, however it lacks a little bit of power and control compared to Ten.

thread_title: Tenenergy 05 vs Donic Baracuda
reply_split: Tenergy often has many complaints of it being incredibly heavy per sheet, but many reviews say it is worth it.

thread_title: Tenenergy 05 vs Donic Baracuda
reply_split: Ultimately, with a heavier top-sheet comes more power, but you can adjust this with your sponge layer.

thread_title: Tenenergy 05 vs Donic Baracuda
reply_split: Baracuda is not as heavy, but in my opinion, just as good.

thread_title: Tenenergy 05 vs Donic Baracuda
reply_split: Tenergy 05 reacts quite a bit to topspin, although if you have an ALL blade, it should be fine.

thread_title: Tenenergy 05 vs Donic Baracuda
reply_split: Baracuda is very good with incoming spin, and would be fine with any blade.

thread_title: Tenenergy 05 vs Donic Baracuda
reply_split: Just remember to keep your bat angle low.

thread_title: Tenenergy 05 vs Donic Baracuda
reply_split: Tenergy has many complaints of it being non-durable.

thread_title: Tenenergy 05 vs Donic Baracuda
reply_split: Some reviewers claim that with only a few days of playing with it, obvious cracks were in the rubber on the side.

thread_title: Tenenergy 05 vs Donic Baracuda
reply_split: Just don't throw it around on the table.

thread_title: Tenenergy 05 vs Donic Baracuda
reply_split: Maybe because the topsheet is a little bit harder.

thread_title: Tenenergy 05 vs Donic Baracuda
reply_split: I can't really comment how easy either one is to use, since they're suited for different playing styles.

thread_title: Tenenergy 05 vs Donic Baracuda
reply_split: Tenergy is noticeably faster than Baracuda, though not quite as spinny.

thread_title: Tenenergy 05 vs Donic Baracuda
reply_split: If driving's your thing, use Tenergy.

thread_title: Tenenergy 05 vs Donic Baracuda
reply_split: If long, spinny rallies is how you tend to lean towards, Baracuda would be a better rubber.

thread_title: Tenenergy 05 vs Donic Baracuda
reply_split: In conclusion,

reply_split: Ten has higher throw angle

reply_split: Ten is heavier

thread_title: Friendship Focus III Snipe / Palio AK47 Blue
reply_split: Hi, I have used the Focus III extensively 5 years ago and recently bought the AK47 Blue.

thread_title: Friendship Focus III Snipe / Palio AK47 Blue
reply_split: For a direct comparison the AK47 Blue is slightly faster but actually significantly less grip so you are not going to get higher throw from it.

thread_title: Friendship Focus III Snipe / Palio AK47 Blue
reply_split: It is also a little bit heavier (but still in the light rubbers category so not too much of a concern).

thread_title: Friendship Focus III Snipe / Palio AK47 Blue
reply_split: For a cheapy with higher surface grip, try the ktl series (pro XP, Rapid Sound etc) both are almost as light and a bit more spinny, speed as with the Focus on the medium-low side.

thread_title: Friendship Focus III Snipe / Palio AK47 Blue
reply_split: I always felt F+S III was a very soft rubber but Palio AK-47 blue is a lot harder and heavier sponge.

thread_title: Friendship Focus III Snipe / Palio AK47 Blue
reply_split: FSIII is better and easier at flat kills and brush loops.

thread_title: Friendship Focus III Snipe / Palio AK47 Blue
reply_split: AK-47 blue is more loop kill and loop drive and needs a very pronounced stroke and not very forgiving.

thread_title: Friendship Focus III Snipe / Palio AK47 Blue
reply_split: I am unable to compare "throw" for either as I tried these rubbers on different blades and felt it was close enough to feel the same.

thread_title: Friendship Focus III Snipe / Palio AK47 Blue
reply_split: AK-47 comes in red,yellow and blue branding and I don't know about the other 2 since have not tried them.

thread_title: Friendship Focus III Snipe / Palio AK47 Blue
reply_split: Thank you man iii and lasta for your replies.I actually went and bought a pair of Gewo Hype EL 40 rubbers in 1.9 sponge about 3 months ago.Have to say I've been very impressed with them so far.

thread_title: Friendship Focus III Snipe / Palio AK47 Blue
reply_split: My game has improved noticeably.They are a tiny bit heavier than the Snipe III but I got used to the weight difference very quickly.They play similar to the Snipe but offer a little more control / placement and a lot more spin.The throw is also slightly higher than the Snipe and the arc is greater too.In fact I would say that they do everything that the Snipe did but just that little bit better in all aspects.Speed, control, spin are all noticeably better with the Hype El 40.Is the Hype EL worth the extra cost compared to the Snipe?All things considered I would say yes.

thread_title: 5Q sound or Andro rasant beat

thread_title: Donic Barracuda or Tibhar Genius sound
reply_split: I did a little search on your blade and it comes up as stiff and fast.A high throw rubber compensates for the stiffness giving a better arc allowing one to land balls on the table more easily.Problem with high throw rubbers is control.

thread_title: Donic Barracuda or Tibhar Genius sound
reply_split: Most opt for medium throw on the BH for control reserving the high throw for the FH.If you're starting off it's not recommended to have a stiff blade and a high throw rubber.The little that I know of pips is that a stiff blade is beneficial.

thread_title: Donic Barracuda or Tibhar Genius sound
reply_split: Personally I would compromise the stiffness for more flexibility allowing you to use medium to low throw rubbers so that you can get your technique right and learn to play more easily with looping etc.So maybe another thread might be needed to see if you could use a less stiff jpen blade ?Normally with a rubber the arc starts to flatten out the harder you hit - only exception that I've found is the Tenergy 05 which I would not recommend for you given the control issues with it.So if you have a slightly harder sponge it tends to keep its arc and in practice is more consistent than a soft sponge.

thread_title: Donic Barracuda or Tibhar Genius sound
reply_split: So depending how you hit the Vega Europe may prove better to play with than the Vega Elite despite having the same throw rating.If you plan on sticking with your current stiff fast jpen blade I would be inclined to use a non tensor technology rubber for better control to allow better development.I've recommended the Stiga Magna TC II before.

thread_title: Which Euro/Jap rubber beats Tenergy for pushing/serving?
reply_split: As I get to return serves all the time from all the top players at our association, the spinniest serves and pushes would come from our Chinese ex-provincial members who use DHS H3 or Haifu Whale... Definitely heavier in spin than T05, perhaps by about 25%... Other non-Chinese rubbers that can produce roughly the same amount of spin as T05 in serves and pushes are Calibra LT, Acuda S1, Stiga Boost TP and Yasaka Rakza 7... Maybe T05 could push heavier than these, but I do not feel it from Zaman M. or Justin N... As a matter of fact I have never felt T05 users could overpower me with extra spin than most other non-Chinese inverted...

thread_title: Which Euro/Jap rubber beats Tenergy for pushing/serving?
reply_split: This is my completely impartial view, despite the fact that I've spoken out against Butterfly's pricing numerous times... Now if T05 users feel they can produce spin easier (and with better control) than its competitors, that could very well be true, but there's definitely a ceiling on this rubber's spin capability that I feel is not superior to many rubbers out there.

thread_title: LKT Pro Xt or XP?
reply_split: The feel of a setup is a very personal choice, decided by both the player's playing style and pure personal preference.

thread_title: LKT Pro Xt or XP?
reply_split: A "mushy" blade can be very good at looping and the short game, but they're generally not good for blocking and hitting.

thread_title: LKT Pro Xt or XP?
reply_split: If Robot Blocker, as his name suggests, is a blocker, then it would be natural for him to prefer a harder blade as they do block more precisely.

thread_title: LKT Pro Xt or XP?
reply_split: A soft and flexible setup has very good control and spin for loops, but as you step up in level and need more speed, then your shots will need to have more hitting components to them(e.g.

thread_title: LKT Pro Xt or XP?
reply_split: loop drives, counter hits, etc.).

thread_title: LKT Pro Xt or XP?
reply_split: THEN, harder setups will be more useful.

thread_title: LKT Pro Xt or XP?
reply_split: Unless you become a hitter/blocker, then hard and flexy setups will be the way to go once you reach that level.

thread_title: LKT Pro Xt or XP?
reply_split: re blade vs rubber combos.

thread_title: LKT Pro Xt or XP?
reply_split: for anyone still learning and discovering what kind of player they will be it's best to use a not very flexible soft allround 5 ply (mushy blade).

thread_title: LKT Pro Xt or XP?
reply_split: Once you get enough skill to engage in long distance rallys you will want to or need to move to a thin flexible blade, if you decide you will play offensively near the table you might be better with a hard feel 7 ply like a clipper with softer rubbers.

thread_title: LKT Pro Xt or XP?
reply_split: The thicker 7 plys don't need heavy rubbers since they don't rely so much on flex, the harder thin and flexible 5 plys do need heavier rubber to induce the flex which lets them play so far from the table.

thread_title: LKT Pro Xt or XP?

thread_title: H2 Neo or Thors?
reply_split: I just started using H2 Neo after having used Tenergy 25 for 4-5 months and seeing a nice rating boost.

thread_title: H2 Neo or Thors?
reply_split: H2 Neo is upping my rating again, due mainly to its greater consistency: My coaches and opponents tell me I'm simply getting more balls on the table.

thread_title: H2 Neo or Thors?
reply_split: And H2 is clearly harder for opponents to deal with; a quality that's not often talked about when inverted rubber is being discussed (it has to do with H2's ball path and kick off the table, as well as its spin variations).H2 Neo's spin on serve is on par with T25, possibly even stronger.

thread_title: H2 Neo or Thors?
reply_split: H2 Neo starts out tacky but it mostly wears off after 5-6 matches and the speed increases as the tackiness decreases.

thread_title: H2 Neo or Thors?
reply_split: Another FH rubber to consider is DHS Skyline TG3 Neo which I'm currently testing.

thread_title: H2 Neo or Thors?
reply_split: Faster and harder than H2 Neo, TG3 Neo is even tackier and seems to have somewhat higher throw, and noticeably more spin on serve.My experience with Palio Thors is mixed.

thread_title: H2 Neo or Thors?
reply_split: I test hit with a brand new sheet some months back and absolutely hated it, as did several other 1800+ players who tried it that day.

thread_title: H2 Neo or Thors?
reply_split: It was very tacky and non-linear, where hard strokes were rockets, but any stroke with less power could unexpectedly land in the net.

thread_title: H2 Neo or Thors?
reply_split: Otoh, I tried another player's well broken in Thors -- so much so that it had a dull spot in the hitting zone -- and was astounded at how different it was than the brand new sheet I had tried previously.

thread_title: H2 Neo or Thors?
reply_split: The broken in Thors was, hands down, the best blocking rubber I had ever used: Effortless high-speed blocks off of blistering incoming drives had me instantly grinning.

thread_title: H2 Neo or Thors?
reply_split: Linearity was fine, and speed and spin were great.

thread_title: H2 Neo or Thors?
reply_split: But whether I want to endure a break-in period that may be dozens of matches long is something I haven't committed to.. yet.

thread_title: H2 Neo or Thors?
reply_split: You can play well with H2 neo or Thors but they are fairly different rubbers and like nathanso said regarding Thors changing with age the difference between them grows with age, the H2 neo will get slower, Thors will get faster.

thread_title: H2 Neo or Thors?
reply_split: A brand new Thors is still faster than H2 neo will ever be and more spinny but once it's got 30, 40 maybe 50 hours on it, then it's quite fast and also very lively.

thread_title: H2 Neo or Thors?
reply_split: I've got a sheet with around 200 hours on it and I still like it more than a new sheet.

thread_title: H2 Neo or Thors?
reply_split: The thing about H2 is that is one of the least side spin reactive rubbers you can get and Thors is possibly the most sidespin reactive rubber you can get, they both make similar topspin but Thors does it more easily and also will curve the ball on sidespin a lot further than H2 can.H2 neo is much easier to control, and again like nathanso said H2 is very difficult for opponents to read the spin and be able to return the ball, because it flys flat with heavy spin it's a very unusual rubber and something almost no one is used to.

thread_title: H2 Neo or Thors?
reply_split: I'm not 100% happy with either H2 or Thors as a complete package and both have flaws which you have to play around.

thread_title: H2 Neo or Thors?
reply_split: In the end I can use either H2 or Thors and play at the same level whatever but Thors is a much more powerful rubber and because you can bend the ball around the net at will and win points from full court length + do all kinds of trick stuff so easily it's much more fun to use so I'll choose it over H2 just for the fun factor since it doesn't cost me points although anywhere much below 2000 us level I think you would be better served with H2 just because it's so much easier to control.

thread_title: H2 Neo or Thors?
reply_split: Make no mistake Thors is harder to use at full pace than any other tensor and any tenergy, it's very demanding but that seems the price you have to pay for a very powerful tacky rubber.The third rubber nathanso mentioned TG3 is probably the best bet for most people since it more side spinny than H2, not quite as deceptive as H2 but is more easy to use than either Thors or H2, it's actually softer in the top sheet than H2 and has the same sponge so any feeling of it being harder is just go old DHS variation or a harder degree sponge.

thread_title: H2 Neo or Thors?
reply_split: The tackiness varies wildly also, some TG3 are very tacky and some aren't hardly tacky at all, just depends on what day it was made, all the red DHS rubbers are more consistant in this way and I only buy red sheets of DHS rubbers now because of that reason, they tend to be "just right", they also last longer The end of the story I think is for you who naturally hits with sidespin.. Buy TG3 neo

thread_title: H2 Neo or Thors?
reply_split: I don't think that can be a bottoming out feeling... the sponge is simply too hard to bottom out IMO.

thread_title: H2 Neo or Thors?
reply_split: The only time you can ever slightly bottom Thors is counter hitting a very well hit ball as hard as you can, I doubt more than 1% of the table tennis population can achieve that kind of speed, it happens a long time after T05 or any of the other famous tensors, when it does happen you can see the ball fly straighter than usual, normally it ends in a long ball even from full court.

thread_title: H2 Neo or Thors?
reply_split: Imho the people that say it bottoms out easily are feeling the rubber and sponge going squirrly because it doesn't bottom out, when you get a rubber and blade combination just right for your power you want it to just kiss the blade on your biggest and best attacking shots, this gives the whole combo a nice stabilising effect and that's what you should always aim for.

thread_title: H2 Neo or Thors?
reply_split: 2.1mm T05 will do that just nicely on the FH of a strong looper and I think it's one of the major reasons it's so popular with good players.

thread_title: H2 Neo or Thors?
reply_split: Thors not being able to do that for anyone near mortal is it's only downfall as far as I can tell.

thread_title: H2 Neo or Thors?
reply_split: It needs to be a bit softer or less tension in the sponge .

thread_title: H2 Neo or Thors?
reply_split: You can still use it just fine as it is as since you only bottom out the really top rubbers on big loops or counter hitting anyway, but it would be just that much better if it was more stable on those mission critical high pressure shots

thread_title: Haifu Shark III / Shark Speed Review

thread_title: Rubber is dead/not playable - needs a change
reply_split: ask yourself: is it playing any different?

thread_title: Rubber is dead/not playable - needs a change
reply_split: Does it grip the ball as it did on the first weeks/months?You can also ask a regular playing partner who knows quite well of how you play.

thread_title: Rubber is dead/not playable - needs a change
reply_split: Ask him if it was any different compare to before.

thread_title: Rubber is dead/not playable - needs a change
reply_split: That's what we do when trying to decide to get new rubbers/equipment or not.

thread_title: Rubber is dead/not playable - needs a change
reply_split: The physical appearance of the rubber can also be a good indicator of how used up it is.

thread_title: Rubber is dead/not playable - needs a change
reply_split: You can often see a significant difference on the rubber surface, if you compare the area where you usually hit the ball to the edges of the rubber or the part nearer the handle which stays relatively new.

thread_title: Rubber is dead/not playable - needs a change
reply_split: If there is a huge difference there it might be time to change the rubber.But more often then not, the best judge is playability.

thread_title: Rubber is dead/not playable - needs a change
reply_split: Are your serves less spinny, loops have less kick in them, then I guess the rubber is dying, but not dead.At the end of the day it is a personal decision, some players change rubbers when they start to change characteristics, since they want to play with the rubber at its peak performance.

thread_title: Rubber is dead/not playable - needs a change
reply_split: And some extract every last bit of juice from their rubbers, something I would not encourage.

thread_title: Rubber is dead/not playable - needs a change
reply_split: As soon as another rubber takes your fancy.....oops, sorry, that's the EJ answer!!

thread_title: Rubber is dead/not playable - needs a change
reply_split: Seriously though, pay attention to how your rubber feels throughout its life in terms of its grippiness (on your serve, loop, chop, etc), its liveliness, how sweet your shots feel, stuff like that.

thread_title: Rubber is dead/not playable - needs a change
reply_split: When you feel dissatisfied with the rubber's performance, its time to change.

thread_title: Rubber is dead/not playable - needs a change
reply_split: Some people find they don't mind playing with a dead-ish rubber and are happy to continue on with it.

thread_title: Rubber is dead/not playable - needs a change
reply_split: Others find that they are surprised how good a new rubber feels against what their previous rubber had slowly degraded to.

thread_title: Rubber is dead/not playable - needs a change
reply_split: I don't think you can put any hard and fast rules on it though.

thread_title: Too fast, or just fast enough?
reply_split: Both still require a good stroke, but I feel the Roxon was just that touch more forgiving.

thread_title: Too fast, or just fast enough?
reply_split: So its control is not always just about the speed, the rubber characteristics can influence the control available at the same speed.

thread_title: Too fast, or just fast enough?
reply_split: Of course, there are other subtle differences too in the way different rubbers can play with respect to this.

thread_title: Too fast, or just fast enough?
reply_split: It's all about the short game for me, and as Yuzuki pointed out best tested in tense conditions.

thread_title: Too fast, or just fast enough?
reply_split: Am I comfortable touching short, can I dig a little extra on an occasional push, can I push an odd ball right off the bounce to get more spin, can I misdirect a push when I see an opponent move, can I receive serve well?

thread_title: Too fast, or just fast enough?
reply_split: Can I do these things without constantly worrying about going too long.If I can do these things I will certainly be OK in the offensive and blocking games (and strangely also chopping away from the table).If I cannot the better players will destroy me with a superior short game- the foundation of a good player's skills.

thread_title: Too fast, or just fast enough?
reply_split: For me it's all about the short game.

thread_title: Too fast, or just fast enough?
reply_split: If I have trouble pushing or blocking then it is too fast.

thread_title: Too fast, or just fast enough?
reply_split: Service spin and how tight I can get the serve.

thread_title: FH rubber for close/mid-distance chopping and attack?
reply_split: The issue with a rubber for chopping is that it doesn't want to be too fast or bouncy otherwise the ball is gone before you get much chance to inflict any great degree of spin on it.

thread_title: FH rubber for close/mid-distance chopping and attack?
reply_split: This means that a thicker sponge will eject the ball out quicker and be worse for chopping.

thread_title: FH rubber for close/mid-distance chopping and attack?
reply_split: Obviously the more grip you get from the topsheet the better, whereas with a looping rubber it can come from the sponge or the topsheet because you can apply more force to the ball as you are giving the ball downward force.

thread_title: FH rubber for close/mid-distance chopping and attack?
reply_split: It is more delicate chopping because you give upward force generally, so you can't rely much on the sponge to provide this, it has to come from the topsheet.

thread_title: FH rubber for close/mid-distance chopping and attack?
reply_split: A chopped ball will float in the air and go further, whereas a topspin ball will be dragged down by the spin force.

thread_title: FH rubber for close/mid-distance chopping and attack?
reply_split: So in seeking a chopping rubber you need to look for a very grippy or tacky topsheet with a thinner or deader sponge.

thread_title: FH rubber for close/mid-distance chopping and attack?
reply_split: Alternatively you can join us on the darkside and use long pimples which vary in the amount of chop spin they create themselves, but take the topspin of the opponent and send it back as underspin when using a chopping action.

thread_title: which is better for flicks (bh)? tenergy 1.9 or 2.1?
reply_split: I think generally a thinner sponge would be better for a flick for the extra control you get and the less catapulting that occurs to send the ball off beyond where you intended.

thread_title: which is better for flicks (bh)? tenergy 1.9 or 2.1?
reply_split: However, I would say the more important thing is having the correct technique and blade angle for the shot and for the rubber and sponge you are using.So overall, I think sponge thickness is not as important as getting the shot right.

thread_title: which is better for flicks (bh)? tenergy 1.9 or 2.1?

thread_title: which is better for flicks (bh)? tenergy 1.9 or 2.1?
reply_split: Because this shot has no backswing or other telltale, when I execute it properly -- particularly on a short ball or unsuspecting serve -- it's usually behind my opponent before they have a chance to even begin moving their paddle.I recently bought Tihbar Nimbus Soft for a med fast 9-ply homemade blade that I use.

thread_title: which is better for flicks (bh)? tenergy 1.9 or 2.1?
reply_split: Paddle Palace convinced me that I didn't want max sponge for my BH so I got the second thickest for BH (in black) and max on the FH (in red).It turns out that there was a noticeable difference in how those two sheets played, particularly on my BH flick/loop.

thread_title: which is better for flicks (bh)? tenergy 1.9 or 2.1?
reply_split: The thinner sponge bottomed out easily and often went long.

thread_title: which is better for flicks (bh)? tenergy 1.9 or 2.1?
reply_split: The max sponge never bottomed out and would take far shorter paths to the table.

thread_title: which is better for flicks (bh)? tenergy 1.9 or 2.1?
reply_split: I was surprised that so little difference in sponge thickness could make such a difference.If you brush loop your flick shots as I sometimes do then sponge thickness isn't nearly as critical (then it's all about keeping your topsheet clean).

thread_title: which is better for flicks (bh)? tenergy 1.9 or 2.1?
reply_split: But if you drive into the ball I think you'll want all the thick, soft sponge you can get.UPDATE: I've since had the chance to hit some more with Tenergy 2.1 and find its dense, springy sponge (which is nothing like Nimbus) virtually impossible to fully compress.. but also (on the right blade) very compelling!

thread_title: Hammond/ Hammond X/ J.O. Platinum
reply_split: Bullets have screwball spin so they basically travel straight independent of spin and speed.

thread_title: Hammond/ Hammond X/ J.O. Platinum
reply_split: Looped table tennis balls travel with topspin, and the flight of the ball varies depending on both the spin and the speed.

thread_title: Hammond/ Hammond X/ J.O. Platinum
reply_split: The faster the ball, the more downward force is applied by the air above the spinning ball.

thread_title: Hammond/ Hammond X/ J.O. Platinum
reply_split: If i recall correctly it's a velocity-squared relation so a 60mph loop experiences four times as much downforce as a 30mph loop.

thread_title: Hammond/ Hammond X/ J.O. Platinum
reply_split: The faster loop will hit the ground before the slower loop.Though ideally you'd want the loop to hit the table, not the ground, and determining whether it's advantageous to hit harder to get more arc is much too complicated to figure in any given situation.

reply_split: I doubt if the amount of spin is much different while the arc is very different.The bullet anolagy was the only one I could think of to try and give an idea about how spin/speed relate.The blade angle required to block a loop tells alot about how much spin is on a ball.Like it was mentioned, another person receiving the ball will have a good idea how much spin was really on the ball.

thread_title: Hammond/ Hammond X/ J.O. Platinum
reply_split: Yes a faster ball has higher momentum, but the momentum is horizontal so it's irrelevant when looking at how quickly the ball will drop.Given two balls with equal rpms and different speeds, the faster ball definitely has a sharper arc, as the force of air resulting from spin is more than gravity.

thread_title: Hammond/ Hammond X/ J.O. Platinum
reply_split: (Whether the sharper arc is enough to overcome the fact that it spends less time over the table is unknown.

thread_title: Hammond/ Hammond X/ J.O. Platinum
reply_split: )Yeah, the person receiving the ball ought to have a good idea of how much spin is really on the ball.

thread_title: Hammond/ Hammond X/ J.O. Platinum
reply_split: However that person also needs to understand how their racket reacts to spin.

thread_title: Hammond/ Hammond X/ J.O. Platinum
reply_split: A more closed racket does not mean the ball has more spin and speed; a lot of times a faster ball with equal spin requires a more open racket.

thread_title: Hammond/ Hammond X/ J.O. Platinum

thread_title: Review Galaxy/Yinhe Venus 36-38deg 2.0mm black (boosted)
reply_split: Hi Hookshot...I have LKT Pro XT which is a tacky rubber as the name says..(XT = extra tacky) and that has remained tackier than it was new for 3 - 4 months now with Spinmax, and an occasional treatment of Eucalyptus Oil and a stint in the sun or under a light for 2 hours brings up that glossy tack that I cannot live without...lol....Its quite dramatic what the EO does and the rubbers just slurp it up...apart from helping maintain tackiness, this EO treatment causes the topsheet to become tuned...Ie the increased size makes the topsheet more dense and adds speed..Anyway, it might not be a bad idea to get some Spinmax Aqueous from Alex...it would be there before you know it, and also try the EO in the sunlight if your sun is warm, or 100 watt light globe at about 12 inches ...watch the heat.I gave a sheet of Mercury (Venus's sister rubber with a Chinese sponge) to a friend a few weeks ago, and he has maintained the rubber tackier than it was at new using the above treatment regime...I do realise I sound a bit like a broken record going on about Spinmax and EO,  but the fact is that they work!!

thread_title: CURRENT TENSOR LIST + Tensor Facts & How to spot a Tenso

thread_title: CURRENT TENSOR LIST + Tensor Facts & How to spot a Tenso
reply_split: The reason tensor are less durable is that the topsheet is applied to the sponge under tension and stretches it.

thread_title: CURRENT TENSOR LIST + Tensor Facts & How to spot a Tenso
reply_split: This thins out the topsheet and makes it more prone to wear.

thread_title: CURRENT TENSOR LIST + Tensor Facts & How to spot a Tenso

thread_title: CURRENT TENSOR LIST + Tensor Facts & How to spot a Tenso
reply_split: Older gen tensors had 2 big problems that the rubber tended to crumble at the edges easily and the material would "oxidize" on its surface if left exposed to the air for too long, making the rubber look "patchy" and dull.

thread_title: CURRENT TENSOR LIST + Tensor Facts & How to spot a Tenso
reply_split: Thus they needed a sticky protective sheet.

thread_title: CURRENT TENSOR LIST + Tensor Facts & How to spot a Tenso

thread_title: CURRENT TENSOR LIST + Tensor Facts & How to spot a Tenso

thread_title: Learning proper technique with flex blade and soft rubber?
reply_split: Serve return is never easy (as you get better, so do the serves of your opponents), and if you have trouble with push/short game, it's hard to recommend a faster set up.You have 3 choices:1.

thread_title: Learning proper technique with flex blade and soft rubber?
reply_split: The natural way: Keep the current setup, replace the "same" rubbers when they get old (6 months).

thread_title: Learning proper technique with flex blade and soft rubber?

thread_title: Learning proper technique with flex blade and soft rubber?
reply_split: Just to give you an update... so I am playing with the new combo Stiga ARC and Rakza 7 for few days now, no matches yet.

thread_title: Learning proper technique with flex blade and soft rubber?
reply_split: First thing I noticed is that the bat is now much heavier with the harder sponge (Rakza 7 vs Samba Plus) but I start to like it and actually feel the old combo rather light/toy version...Second thing is that it is much more difficult to impart spin, particularly underspin on pushing, at the same time I start to feel it is much less sensitive to incoming underspin...

thread_title: Learning proper technique with flex blade and soft rubber?
reply_split: It is like the ball is leaving my racket much more flat now, i.e.

thread_title: Learning proper technique with flex blade and soft rubber?
reply_split: does not bounce much to the net or long, at the same time very difficult to make a super floating spinny push just above the net...

thread_title: Learning proper technique with flex blade and soft rubber?
reply_split: But overall less risky, more control, still need to learn to adjust the height of my shots...In blocks/drives I start to feel actually more control, In topspn, definitely harder to impart spin.. difficult to make high arc, but I start to feel that I can hit harder and the ball actually flies lower and still hits the table, so more dangerous to the opponent...I guess I need to train much more and also adjust my movements to the new rubber, But in summary quite happy and looking forward to play further.I would be interested to hear if this is what you would expect after such transition or if what I describe is rather surprising to you...(I will let you know again in few weeks time and hopefully also after some matches...)All the best, David

thread_title: Sriver and Mark V - 51 years and 49 years
reply_split: Armstrong made Satoh's bat - the Japanese Penhold bat with the 5/16" thick bare yellow sponge, with which he won the World Champs (1952 IIRC).

thread_title: Sriver and Mark V - 51 years and 49 years
reply_split: And then this gave rise to many companies experimenting with sponge - mostly bare, mostly very thick.

thread_title: Sriver and Mark V - 51 years and 49 years
reply_split: Towards the end of the 1950s it was mainly a few Japanese players who were experimenting with what we know of today as "sponge rubber" but was referred to back then as "sandwich" - sponge (thinner than was normal) underneath regular hard rubber.

thread_title: Sriver and Mark V - 51 years and 49 years
reply_split: Sometimes the rubber was inverted.

thread_title: Sriver and Mark V - 51 years and 49 years
reply_split: This was also a time of great turmoil and conflict - some tournaments banned sponge, I saw a photo of players holding a demonstration outside one of them, and there was a huge amount of animosity between "spongers" and traditionalists.

thread_title: Sriver and Mark V - 51 years and 49 years
reply_split: Since ANYTHING could be used, where sponge was allowed, there was a huge range in what people brought, and it was getting increasingly difficult to predict what was coming back at you.

thread_title: Sriver and Mark V - 51 years and 49 years
reply_split: So in 1959 ITTF decided to limit the choices of surface to four - hardbat, sandwich, inverted sandwich and bare wood.

thread_title: Sriver and Mark V - 51 years and 49 years
reply_split: And sandwich/inverted sandwich was limited to 4mm thickness.

thread_title: Sriver and Mark V - 51 years and 49 years
reply_split: This came from the Japanese experiments with sandwich, it was seen to be viable, though IIRC the Japanese actually wanted more thickness (6mm IIIRC).

thread_title: Sriver and Mark V - 51 years and 49 years
reply_split: THIS was when the likes of Butterfly, Yasaka, Nittaku, Armstrong, et al.

thread_title: Sriver and Mark V - 51 years and 49 years
reply_split: began marketing the sort of "soft rubber" that we're familiar with today.

thread_title: Sriver and Mark V - 51 years and 49 years

thread_title: What is the ideal rubber for services and pushes?
reply_split: There IS NOT a single rubber optimized for this, not matter what tt company marketing one may hear.Everyone has a different impact and acceleration, so it can vary.If you do not catch the ball in the topsheet and throw it out to make your spin, then a tacky rubber will give you easier results.For me, a topsheet that has a really dynamic stretching topsheet makes it super easy for me to get spin on both serves and brush type loops.

thread_title: What is the ideal rubber for services and pushes?
reply_split: it is a bonus that the topsheet is a little worn and less spin sensitive, so I can add spin in my way vs incoming spin.I have used inexpensive rubbers like Dawei XP 2008 Super Power (nor big power, just big control) and modern dynamic rubbers equally well for this.Your ability to catch and throw the ball and your ability to control grip pressure at impact will have much more say in the result than just your rubber/blade, but yes, appropriate equipment makes it EASIER to do some things.

thread_title: What is the ideal rubber for services and pushes?
reply_split: QNB,The key to selling any spin on any serve is the ability to use the same service motion and strike the ball at a different point.

thread_title: What is the ideal rubber for services and pushes?
reply_split: It doesn't hurt for the stroke to be smooth and have after motions different from what the ball looks like.For a topspin serve on a FH pendulum, one contacts the ball right on the up portion of the pendulum striking the bottom back of the ball.

thread_title: What is the ideal rubber for services and pushes?
reply_split: A very light touch and light grip at impact is needed to keep the topspin serve short and low.That serve, if you can pull it off, looks just like your underspin serve and will get you a ball to attack, sometimes an error on receive.

thread_title: What is the ideal rubber for services and pushes?
reply_split: Just don't overuse it too much in a match.Making a low/tight dead ball look like your heavy or medium underspin could probably become your go-to point getter if your normal underspin serve has any decent underspin.

thread_title: Review of Donic Acuda S1 Turbo and Hexer HD
reply_split: I have tried Acuda S1 Turbo recently, and decided to write down some thoughts on it with comparison to my other tensor rubber, Xiom Omega IV Asia (doesn't exactly comply with the title of this thread but I couldn't find any other review for S1 Turbo, sorry; hope it's OK)Weight: about the same, around 45 g for a cut sheetTackiness: none on bothHardness: same, Medium-Hard sponge, about 47-48 on ESN scaleSpeed: rather deceptive, since Acuda is less linear.

thread_title: Review of Donic Acuda S1 Turbo and Hexer HD
reply_split: It is about as fast as O4A on fast attacking shots but often much slower on slow and midpower placement shots.Tensor/Catapult: noticeably more pronounced on Acuda.Control: pretty good on both, but better on O4ASpin: better on Acuda for all strokes but fast loopsSensitivity: better (less sensitive) for O4AFlat game: slightly better for O4ALooping: opening loops better for Acuda, counterlooping and fast loopkills - some advantage for O4AShort game: about the same but O4A is a bit more predictable for me, produces less unexpected pushes into the netBackhand game: O4A is better since usually people play more placement shots, pushes and placement shots on BH , and O4A beats Acuda thereI would recommend Acuda over O4A only to the players who are heavily spin-oriented and rarely do "soft" strokes on their FH (except an opening loop).

thread_title: Regluing tensor and tensor-like rubbers
reply_split: seeping in at a much faster and higher rate, after brushing the P.O., leave the sponge soaking for about 30 mins to 1 hour and then later on come back with WD-40, a plastic ziplock bag and a plastic sheet cut-out from the rubber packaging.

thread_title: Regluing tensor and tensor-like rubbers
reply_split: Then Spray WD-40 very close on the sponge while getting a LOT of "liquid" WD-40 sitting on the sponge, immediately cover it with the plastic sheet, put it all in the ZipLoc bag and seal it with the sponge facing up.

thread_title: Regluing tensor and tensor-like rubbers
reply_split: If you want you can now Stack HUGE weights on it which will "squish" out the air, but the liquid will still seep in.

thread_title: Regluing tensor and tensor-like rubbers
reply_split: And then remove the weights after a while, which should allow the sponge to expand and suck in more of the P.O.

thread_title: Can I get your thoughts on 1.7/1.8 & 2.0 setup? & recommend
reply_split: You don't want to buy a slow racket and fast rubbers to begin, what you want to do is find a setup that allows you to do all shots comfortably but doesn't mask mistakes in your technique by being too much of an aid (especially if you are trying to increase your level).Some forum members may disagree but I always suggest Max rubbers on both sides no matter the level unless...A) you have a strength problem and need to decrease the weight of the blade.B) you are a chopper who will chop/loop in a ratio of 300/1 on the forehand.The feeling of control does not come from the speed of the ball but from the ability of the ball to sink through the topsheet, through the sponge and just be felt gently by the blade.

thread_title: Tacky rubbers and booster/factory tuning/glueing
reply_split: ":(Usually), booster/tuning is applied to the blade side of the sponge and then begins leaking, from there, into and through the sponge and then out into the air.So, the boosting/tuning is stronger and remains stronger nearer the blade, and is weaker (and then gets even weaker) on the topsheet side, where the booster/tuner leaks out.If the sponge is hard, and if the topsheet side of the sponge is *relatively* unboosted/untuned, then the gap (as described above) between topsheet mode and sponge mode would be preserved to some extent for the sake of the short game, while a harder hit would engage the more boosted/tuned sponge farther down.

thread_title: Air DefenderS and AssassinS
reply_split: Whether you do a push-style chop or a full-on side of the body JSK FH chop, the ball went back with an immense amount of spin.

thread_title: Air DefenderS and AssassinS
reply_split: The balls kept popping back out of the ball catch due to the backspin, and often ramped out and got air.

thread_title: Air DefenderS and AssassinS
reply_split: It’s safe to take a big stroke, but you have to adjust your angle because the throw becomes higher with racket speed.

thread_title: Air DefenderS and AssassinS
reply_split: (Other less grippy rubbers don’t require as much attention in throw angle) To clarify, throw angle on chops is downward because the stroke is going downward, and therefore ball trajectory is lower and risks hitting the net.

thread_title: Air DefenderS and AssassinS
reply_split: Blocks seem to have good pace, vs. Reflectoid which has more of a dampening feel.

thread_title: Air DefenderS and AssassinS
reply_split: However the Defender was slow enough vs. hard/fast loops, and fast enough that it seems the opponent will have to pay attention.

thread_title: Air DefenderS and AssassinS
reply_split: I really cranked up the robot, and didn’t notice any bottoming out and certainly no change in throw angle as you get from other thin rubbers when the ball makes contact with the blade.

thread_title: Air DefenderS and AssassinS
reply_split: On active forward strokes, the rubber was much faster than I was expecting.

thread_title: Air DefenderS and AssassinS
reply_split: It loops well; the throw is medium to medium low.

thread_title: Air DefenderS and AssassinS
reply_split: I was VERY surprised how fast it was on offense!

thread_title: Rasant Grip and Powergrip
reply_split: You quickly learn a couple of things.

thread_title: Rasant Grip and Powergrip
reply_split: First, RASANTs are FAST.

thread_title: Rasant Grip and Powergrip
reply_split: Second, if you want a soft sponge, forget RASANTs.

thread_title: Rasant Grip and Powergrip
reply_split: Slide the Fast slider any more than about 15% to the left and all the RASANTs disappear.

thread_title: Rasant Grip and Powergrip
reply_split: Slide the Hard slider any more than about 35% to the left and all the RASANTs disappear.

thread_title: Rasant Grip and Powergrip
reply_split: But they aren't the hardest, fastest andros - those are actually the ROXONS - ROXON 500 being the king of hard and fast.

thread_title: Rasant Grip and Powergrip
reply_split: Among the five RASANTs, Powersponge is the slowest, with the softest sponge (but it's still pretty hard compared to other rubbers in the andro line).

thread_title: Rasant Grip and Powergrip
reply_split: Powergrip is the fastest, followed by Turbo.

thread_title: Rasant Grip and Powergrip
reply_split: Then comes Grip and Plain (RASANT), in that order.

thread_title: Rasant Grip and Powergrip
reply_split: For sponge hardness, it's in the same order.

thread_title: Rasant Grip and Powergrip
reply_split: It is interesting that between Plain and Grip on the hard/fast side and Powersponge on the soft/slow side are a bunch of Hexers and Shifters and whatnot.

thread_title: Rasant Grip and Powergrip
reply_split: Even something called Rocket.

thread_title: Rasant Grip and Powergrip
reply_split: So perhaps for the lower level player Powersponge would be the best choice, if he/she really needed a RASANT.

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory
reply_split: We are in this boat together...My interpretation and findings:While there is some correlation between high throw and high arc, they are not exactly the same.

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory
reply_split: Throw angle: Ball's exit angle from the bat, caused by "spin strokes".

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory
reply_split: IOW, the bat's capacity to "drag the ball sideways" with thin/brush strokes.

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory
reply_split: Arc: High arc means that the rubber enables higher spin/speed ratio, so you can make more spin without the ball going faster, giving the ball trajectory a tighter curve.In play:High arc means that it's easier to return safely with topspin, using the spin to bend the trajectory over the net and down on the other side.

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory
reply_split: Low arc (or "long trajectory") gives a less safe but more dangerous return (harder to get to, and to attack, because flatter trajectory gives lower bounce).

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory
reply_split: High throw means that energy from lateral movement (thin strokes, and incoming spin) is better conserved.

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory
reply_split: This enables you to use the opponent's speed/spin as an energy source (i.e.

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory
reply_split: you use less energy, passive blocks are faster), but you are also more vulnerable to incoming spin.

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory
reply_split: i don't think a lot of people understand these newer terms like like arc and throw.

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory
reply_split: so.

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory
reply_split: We usually mean topsin in this context but sidespin balls also "arc".

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory
reply_split: However if I do a passive block (for example) the ball does not go deep due to the dead sponge.

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory
reply_split: Keme correctly describes the throw angle - simple the angle the ball leaves the bat given the same ball for two different bats.Arc is the flight of the ball.

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory
reply_split: Given the same strike of the ball with either bat... A high arc means the ball travels higher and drops on table.

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory
reply_split: A low arc means the ball travels lower and hits the table.Generally, the high arc rubbers have the higher degree of spin.

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory
reply_split: Yet, even a low arc rubber (like Calibra) can have exteme spin at the high end of speed on fast loops while keeping a low flight path.

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory
reply_split: Such a rubber could have the same amount of spin as a shot by a player using T05, but the shot by the player with Calibra can make the speed faster to result in a ball with more extreme speed than T05 and around the same amount of spin.To confuse things even more, a player who hits the ball a little flatter than the classic spinner can make a very low arc shot loaded with spin, a similar trajectory as Calibra, but this happens if the player knows how to strike the ball differently in a manner to produce this shot.

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory
reply_split: I know that Tenergy 05 for example is not that fast compared to many other rubbers these days, but to keep the ball on the table I use a more closed racket angle when looping or driving than I would with quite a few other offensive rubbers.

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory
reply_split: I also know T05 generates a lot of spin.

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory
reply_split: But trying to extract all of these parameters is, for me at least, really hard.

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory
reply_split: So when I play with a different rubber I really am only able to decide two things: If I like its performance and if I like its feel.

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory
reply_split: To figure that out, I try to address the following questions, which usually are easy to understand and have clear answers: Can I keep the ball on the table?

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory
reply_split: Is my attack effective and is there an acceptable margin for error?

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory
reply_split: By effective attack I ask, does my opponent have trouble keeping some of my heavier loops on the table and judging their spin correctly, and can my faster drives penetrate their defense?

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory
reply_split: How often do I make unforced errors by missing long attempting those shots?

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory
reply_split: Can I serve, return serve, and effectively play short or off-speed balls and flicks?

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory
reply_split: Is blocking effective and comfortable and again, how much margin for error is there, and if I don't have my racket angle perfect am I hosed or is there a chance the ball goes on anyway?

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory
reply_split: Is the racket angle I have to use for a given shot make sense to my intuitions honed over decades of play and is it comfortable?There are always tradeoffs, you have to keep that in mind.The advantage is that none of these questions uses words or phrases of uncertain meaning, which means if I use them in a review, other people will understand.

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory
reply_split: I can also say whether the rubber feels hard or soft (and if a blade is stiff or flexible).

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory
reply_split: Trying to extract more of the physics going on is pretty much impossible to me as a player.

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory
reply_split: And even if I could do it confidently (which I can't), would other people know what I am saying if I use some of these terms?

thread_title: Throw angle and arc trajectory
reply_split: Maybe not.So when I review equipment in the future, I promise to avoid using terms like throw angle, although I have been guilty of using them in the past.

thread_title: Rubber suggestions for slow loop and mid distance
reply_split: There's no magic rubber for this... What you have to do is to further understand the characteristics of your rubber and adjust your technique accordingly.

thread_title: Rubber suggestions for slow loop and mid distance
reply_split: Say you could do the slow spinny loop against underspin at the table very well with the 729-08, but could not counter loop successfully against a heavy loop with it.

thread_title: Rubber suggestions for slow loop and mid distance
reply_split: The thing to understand is your counter looping technique is most likely off when you use this rubber.

thread_title: Rubber suggestions for slow loop and mid distance
reply_split: Because of the fact that 729-08 is more spinny than the Outlaw, you have to accelerate your racket speed to add even more topspin to your counter loop to bring the ball down.

thread_title: Rubber suggestions for slow loop and mid distance
reply_split: So a successful counter loop with 729-08 will look faster, spinnier and stronger than an Outlaw's.

thread_title: Rubber suggestions for slow loop and mid distance
reply_split: You simply can't perform a medium-speed counter loop consistently with 729-08 like you could with Outlaw (or Tenergy), but you could perform a fast and powerful counter loop time and time again.

thread_title: Rubber suggestions for slow loop and mid distance
reply_split: Does it make sense?On to the other point: If you can't perform a spinny loop off the push with Outlaw as well as with a 729-08, it means you are not brushing fast enough as required by Outlaw's characteristics, even though it was sufficient when you use a 729-08.

thread_title: Rubber suggestions for slow loop and mid distance
reply_split: So you need to adjust your thinking by accepting your current rubber's properties, in order to develop necessary techniques to make it work as you desire.

thread_title: Rubber suggestions for slow loop and mid distance
reply_split: I have tried thors (for about 5 or so months, but before I had consistent coaching the last 15 months) and found that although faster and more powerful and spinnier than the 729-08 ES, it suffered the same inability to counter loop off the table with my technique.

thread_title: The hype and merit of modern rubbers
reply_split: Glue effect rubbers have 2 significant advantages: + more spin & speed = high quality topspin with little effort = good for consistency and recovery+ You can attack pretty much anything which isn't possible with regular rubbers without very good technical skills, a super fast hand and very good legs as glue effect rubbers are much more forgiving.However, here's the big downside of the story:- very expensive if you play on higher levels as you have to replace your rubbers after 3 weeks- When watching average level TT where glue effect rubbers are getting more and more popular (on lower levels most people rightfully still use classical rubbers), I get the impression that many players should rethink their game and ask themselves the question whether glue effect rubbers are really good for their particular game, as the game usually gets too fast for the players and the control of out of position emergency rescue shots isn't nearly as good as with slower regular rubbers.

thread_title: The hype and merit of modern rubbers
reply_split: Also it's much more difficult to slow the game down if needed.Personally I like glue effect rubbers, but I can't spend this much money on my hobby every year so I've opted out and use H3 and Sriver on TBS again.

thread_title: The hype and merit of modern rubbers
reply_split: I have been thinking a little bit more about this and was trying to compare what it was like 15 years ago vs. now, and these new peppier rubbers have changed one dynamic huge in the game of table tennis.

thread_title: The hype and merit of modern rubbers
reply_split: 15 years ago half the battle was getting to the point where you were hitting the ball, and you had turned your opponent into a blocker.

thread_title: The hype and merit of modern rubbers
reply_split: When you got your opponent into the position of having to block it was quite unlikely that he/she was going to reverse back the advantage into their favor in the exchange (relying almost solely on you making an unforced error).

thread_title: The hype and merit of modern rubbers
reply_split: These new rubbers have really changed the game in that there's a constant threat of pressure which comes directly from the equipment that your opponent has that wouldn't necessarily be there 15 years ago.

thread_title: The hype and merit of modern rubbers
reply_split: I can hit a nice loop, that if I placed it decent should give me an advantage on the table from that point on, but one great placed block and I could immediately be in trouble.

thread_title: The hype and merit of modern rubbers
reply_split: I used to love it when I turned my opponent into a consistent blocker.

thread_title: The hype and merit of modern rubbers
reply_split: That meant they had very few answers for what I was doing.

thread_title: The hype and merit of modern rubbers
reply_split: The same case is still kinda true today, but I fear blocks way more now than I did years ago.

thread_title: The hype and merit of modern rubbers
reply_split: I think you are giving modern rubbers too much credit but, in any case, 15 years ago we had glue which really did make a genuine difference.

reply_split: I wholeheartedly agree with this.

thread_title: DHS Hurricane 3 Neo Comments and Questions
reply_split: I was able to play a full day with Hurricane 3 Num 19 sponge and coming of hexer it took me some time getting used to.

thread_title: DHS Hurricane 3 Neo Comments and Questions
reply_split: At first the tackiness of the rubber was too much and even when warming up I would barely pass the ball, but after 15 mins it started to break in and it was gaining more and more speed.

thread_title: DHS Hurricane 3 Neo Comments and Questions
reply_split: Overall I really love this rubber its slower than hexer on most aspects of all aspects of the game except when looping close to the table, in terms of spin Hexer has more spin but not that much, In control at first I though this rubber has lousy control, I could barely block with it, My FH Chops were hitting the net, and Mid Distance looping was impossible.

thread_title: DHS Hurricane 3 Neo Comments and Questions
reply_split: But after 1 hour of persistence it all paid off, Hurricane requires you to play with active strokes, which not only makes your game better but you put more spin and speed on the ball, when blocking it must be with an active stroke with hexer I would just put the blade still and block, with Hurricane you must guide your block, give it a little push this gives you the power to place that block anywhere on the table.

thread_title: DHS Hurricane 3 Neo Comments and Questions
reply_split: When FH chopping with Andro I was doing it lazy, a soft FH chop which would get in but would not disturb my opponent, with Hurricane you must do proper technique and you can really chop that ball without fear and my parter who is a 2 winged looper who's 500 points ahead of me was visibly not so consistent putting balls back, he immediately asked me "Thats not Hexer right"?.

thread_title: DHS Hurricane 3 Neo Comments and Questions
reply_split: And on looping from mid distance you must get under the ball a little bit since the rubber is so linear.

thread_title: DHS Hurricane 3 Neo Comments and Questions
reply_split: Overall I can say this is my new FH rubber, Im glad i found it since Hexer will be soon at a higher price.

thread_title: DHS Hurricane 3 Neo Comments and Questions
reply_split: So to conclude  speed hexrer control H3 Chop H3 Loop H3 Top Spin Hexer If you depend on speed then hurricane isn't for you, but if you are a modern defensive player that needs consistency of your FH to constantly chop , fish and return balls sent to your FH then H3 is a great alternative.

thread_title: Favorite inverted for chopping and loop
reply_split: In loop, one wants to impart spin while applying some speed to the ball, in chopping, one wants not to impart speed and spin, but rather one wants to moderate the speed to a lower speed than a loop and still spin it a lot.

thread_title: Favorite inverted for chopping and loop
reply_split: These thin rubbers achieve that, and one has to make firm contact to get that kind of spin.

thread_title: Favorite inverted for chopping and loop
reply_split: The thinner rubber allows firmer contact on a chop than the brushing motion on a loop.

thread_title: Favorite inverted for chopping and loop
reply_split: Therefore, I don't think that thin rubber is a good choice for chopping and looping.

thread_title: Favorite inverted for chopping and loop

thread_title: Innova, Innova Light and Innova Premium
reply_split: Innova Ultra Light:-definitely very light-a bit slower and with softer sponge than the regular Innova-it's quick, I would rate speed at about Mark V level, not a speed demon-control is very good-in-game spin is somewhat lacking (topsheet doesn't seem to grippy to me)-mechanical spin not amazing-brush-loops work, but I can ussually get double the spin from say a Tackiness CII or Sun.-serves are controlled but not very spinny-one great thing is that is quite immune to incoming spin: easy to hit through chops and heavy loops.-throw is medium-high-hitting is also good-blocking is just ok-this rubber needs to be played on a flexible blade, it's just horrible on stiff blades (might have something to do with bottoming out)The regular Innova is very similar: bit faster and a bit harder sponge, maybe a bit more linear as well.Overall they are good ALL+ rubbers, but nothing amazing.

thread_title: Durability and Lifespan
reply_split: This is quite an old thread (almost a year old) but asked a very similar questionviewtopic.php?f=9&t=7952&hilit=+joolaTo a degree, how long a rubber actually lasts and how long a rubber feels like it lasts may be two different but equally valid questions.

thread_title: Durability and Lifespan
reply_split: I know different people who use the same rubber but change them at different times.

thread_title: Durability and Lifespan
reply_split: Also some players will use the same rubber sheet for a whole season or longer, some change every couple of months, some more regularly.

thread_title: Durability and Lifespan
reply_split: Their style, how hard they hit the ball, how much they spin the ball, ability and cost will all determine when they change the rubber.

thread_title: Durability and Lifespan
reply_split: Also, if a rubber changes gradually, you may adapt with it without realising and it's only when you use a new sheet of that rubber that it hits home just how much the old sheet you've been using has changed - so it's not just the rubber itself which needs to be considered.On the brighter side for pips players, I don't think I've ever got rid of a sheet of short pips rubber because it's lost its durability or it's lifespan has expired - thinking about it I have some pretty old sheets of short pip rubber now!

thread_title: Durability and Lifespan
reply_split: That rule of thumb is still correct in general (barring any intimate bat/table relationships occuring), however keep in mind that some rubbers go faster and some slower than others.

thread_title: Durability and Lifespan
reply_split: For example, 3rd and 3.5 gen tensors (ie, tango, old donic f, revo quad, cor, etc) tended to lose their spring reasonably rapidly.

thread_title: Durability and Lifespan

thread_title: Durability and Lifespan

thread_title: Durability and Lifespan

thread_title: Durability and Lifespan
reply_split: I would not be surprised if you got 6 mths out of a sheet playing 4 times a week.The rule was (iirc) really meant to apply to a speedgluing looper.

thread_title: Durability and Lifespan
reply_split: Even though we can't glue anymore, it still applies for the majority of glue sound rubbers since they're all more highly strung than regular stuff.

thread_title: Durability and Lifespan
reply_split: For example, if I played 4 times a week, I wouldn't really be changing a sheet of unglued, untuned, un-whatevered Sriver 4 times a year.

thread_title: Durability and Lifespan
reply_split: Additionally, different styles can make a rubber last longer.

thread_title: Durability and Lifespan
reply_split: A looper will wear the grip of the rubber out faster than a hitter, but the hitter would probably suffer a loss of spring from the sponge faster than the hitter.

thread_title: Durability and Lifespan
reply_split: In summary: YMMV.

thread_title: Saturn and Apollo
reply_split: It also has a nice "broken" noise when you smash or "hit flat" and it is noisier than BWII.

thread_title: Saturn and Apollo
reply_split: Compared to my previous rubber, the Apollo produces a little bit less back spin, but on the other hand, I could impart more lift when topspinning the ball.

thread_title: Saturn and Apollo

thread_title: Saturn and Apollo

thread_title: Saturn and Apollo

thread_title: Saturn and Apollo

thread_title: Saturn and Apollo
reply_split: Indeed, with its execellent control, I was not afraid to attack agressively with top spins and we really had great great rallies and he had a hell of a time dealing with the spin of my attacks.Anyway, to make it short : _ very good spin possibilities_ Apollo shines when attacking with topspins_ great control in passive game (short or defensive)_ nice feel thanks to the soft sponge and top sheetI did not think I'd be back to a factory tuned rubber as the tuning effect does not last long but as I pay my Apollo's 16$ I think it is worth it.

thread_title: Poll: Tacky and NonTacky
reply_split: Hi Reb...I wanted the Big Slam sponge for its softness and slowness...so once removed from the donic topsheet and added to the SP topsheet...its a great combo for me...I am not trying to create a tensor effect.if anyone wants to try removing the sponge from the topsheet, there is a special technique, as all heat type removal processes such as Iron and hair dryer and 100 watt light bulb close to the rubber, don't work...and the Big Slam sponge is a little fragile...To get the sponge off I had to find a flat receptacle that would hold the sheet of Donic flat down, and then cover the complete Big Slam sheet of rubber with Thinners and leave it there for 15 minutes or more, and then the topsheet comes off very easily...and it does not make the finished product illegal because its not a topsheet, its a sponge..After removal I place the sponge under a 100 watt light globe...ie a desk lamp turned on and about 75 mm from the bench top and then place the sponge there to get it very hot and completely dried out...its easy to tell if the thinners has gone because it has no thinners smell left...fosss============================

thread_title: FH rubber for close/mid-distance chopping and attack?
reply_split: The issue with a rubber for chopping is that it doesn't want to be too fast or bouncy otherwise the ball is gone before you get much chance to inflict any great degree of spin on it.

thread_title: FH rubber for close/mid-distance chopping and attack?
reply_split: This means that a thicker sponge will eject the ball out quicker and be worse for chopping.

thread_title: FH rubber for close/mid-distance chopping and attack?
reply_split: Obviously the more grip you get from the topsheet the better, whereas with a looping rubber it can come from the sponge or the topsheet because you can apply more force to the ball as you are giving the ball downward force.

thread_title: FH rubber for close/mid-distance chopping and attack?
reply_split: It is more delicate chopping because you give upward force generally, so you can't rely much on the sponge to provide this, it has to come from the topsheet.

thread_title: FH rubber for close/mid-distance chopping and attack?
reply_split: A chopped ball will float in the air and go further, whereas a topspin ball will be dragged down by the spin force.

thread_title: FH rubber for close/mid-distance chopping and attack?
reply_split: So in seeking a chopping rubber you need to look for a very grippy or tacky topsheet with a thinner or deader sponge.

thread_title: FH rubber for close/mid-distance chopping and attack?
reply_split: Alternatively you can join us on the darkside and use long pimples which vary in the amount of chop spin they create themselves, but take the topspin of the opponent and send it back as underspin when using a chopping action.

reply_split: but as far as my knowledge goes, the reason there is no rubber that is super spinny and equally fast because when a rubber has more speed, no matter how tacky the topsheet is, the ball doesn't stay on the rubber very long so the rubber doesn't contact the ball very long and the rubber does not impart much spin on the ball because of the hard sponge.but although a soft rubber does allow the ball to dig into the sponge and let the inverted pimples can impart spin on the ball, softer sponges does not make much speed as hard rubbers.

thread_title: BEST TENSOR / GLUE EFFECT RUBBER FOR SPINNY PUSHES AND CHOPS
reply_split: from RITC.The problem with tensors is that they are way to springy and therefore you cannot generate enough underspin.You see the same problem when returning serves with tensors the ball jumps instead of sways away from the rubber.I myself have switched from soft tensor rubbers to hars tensor rubbers.I have switched from silver to Tenergy in FH and Platin in BH.Tenergy is on the other hand very spinny both extremely hard and fast and therefore it might be impossible to control as a chopper.They do only sell Tenergy to very good players since it is hard to control this hard rubber in the bh.Platin is also medium hard and also very fast it will be way to fast to control in the bh for chopping - that`s why you could not get any soin from it the contact time is very short for this rubber.Both these rubbers are attackers rubbers not choppers.What do you play at the moment ?

thread_title: Yasaka Pryde and Fusion
reply_split: I recently bought a sheet of 2mm Yasaka pryde for my forehand and tried in on Yasaka Malin Carbon and Extra blade and ultimately chose to put on the Extra blade.

thread_title: Yasaka Pryde and Fusion
reply_split: I had some adjusting to do since I was using 999N (unglued) and the rubber characteristics are quite different.Basic Characteristics:-------------------------Very bouncy even on Extra and very loud noise during rallying.

thread_title: Yasaka Pryde and Fusion
reply_split: The control on the setup is very good in blocking and hitting.

thread_title: Yasaka Pryde and Fusion
reply_split: Everyone who tried it said it had great control with on the MLC.Using MLC countering at mid distance was effortless but I opted to use it on Extra because of better control on my backhand for my RPB using V-Stage.

thread_title: Yasaka Pryde and Fusion
reply_split: With the Extra you really have to swing to get decent speed.To get most out of this rubber you have to take full swings or the ball is liable to fly off the table (you will get great control).

thread_title: Yasaka Pryde and Fusion
reply_split: I found I could use the same stroke I used for 999N for Pryde.

thread_title: Yasaka Pryde and Fusion
reply_split: The sponge is not that soft so it can handle the hits.I still need to figure out how to use it for attacking heavy chops if you don't hit it actively the spin bites into the grippy rubber and then it goes into the net.

thread_title: Yasaka Pryde and Fusion
reply_split: This rubber is not good if you are tentative.

thread_title: Yasaka Pryde and Fusion
reply_split: So far it's pretty good for serving as its topsheet is quite grippy.I would highly recommend it as it is fun to play with and it complements my 999N very well.Ted

thread_title: Yasaka Pryde and Fusion
reply_split: I have a sweeping full stroke and pryde fit in better.

thread_title: Yasaka Pryde and Fusion

reply_split: Yes...Well this gluing is all new territory for me...I have Ecolod many times before but I have never had the softness with Ecolo sponges that Falco gives with the Globe rubber and the F3 rubberre the softness...I am not sure what to expect, as I have never glued before..only Ecolod...but with the Falco'd Globe999Nat sponge, I can press hard with my thumb and a slight indentation remains for for at least a 1/2 minute...very strange but it does return to normal after a while...A ball would never have the force or duration of a hard thumb push, but I cannot help but think that this third layer of Falco may have actually slowed the rubber down...but that does not concern me actually..I am more concerned with spin for my game...If you do a smash shot with any rubber it will go hard and fast...perhaps the softness will help direct the ball to the table, instead of pinging off to anywhere but the table...anyway, I will know soon enough...I will take 3 bats with me in case the Globe is uncontrollable...but I imagine that it will be just what I wantI have Falco'd the Ecolod F3 and it definitely is softer to a hard thumb push, but no indent remains for any length of timeas far as tackiness goes...I would give it to the Globe by a few seconds...about 1/3 as long again...Then again...spininess is not directly related to Tackiness, ...the fact that the globe compresses with the soft sponge must mean that it grabs around the ball and creates more spin that way...I have not had a hit with it since I put the third layer on...It could be a spin MONSTERLOL...Ha!!
